## RELEASE STRATEGY: FREEING THE DROP

### OPTION A: FULL DROP — "SIN MIEDO"
Release the album as-is. Title the campaign "Sin Miedo" (without fear). Angel's mother's creed becomes the marketing hook. Risk level: HIGH. Reward: Establishes Dog-Prophet as a legitimate artist and SD Media as international. The E-Boy feature stays buried in the tracklist — casual listeners won't know it's Stray.

### OPTION B: REDACTED DROP — "DOG GONE PROFIT [CENSORED]"
Release with Track 06 heavily redacted (the REDACTED in Angel's real name stays redacted, RICO references removed). The E-Boy is credited but not identified. Lux's phone call is pitched beyond recognition. Risk level: MEDIUM. Reward: Album drops without exposing anyone, but loses emotional impact.

### OPTION C: PROPHETFILMS VISUAL DROP
Don't release the album as music. Release ProphetFilms Stream 01 as a FILM — a documentary about Angel's arrival in London, with the music as soundtrack. The visual context gives deniability ("it's art, it's documentary, it's not a gang manifesto"). Risk level: LOW-MEDIUM. Reward: Builds Angel's brand as filmmaker/artist, positions SD Media as a creative collective rather than just a rap label. Dame would love this — it's HER medium.

### OPTION D: THE LEAK
The album "accidentally" surfaces online. No official release. No one claims responsibility. It builds underground buzz. SD Media can deny involvement while benefiting from the exposure. Risk level: CHAOTIC. Reward: Street credibility. The vaulted-then-leaked narrative becomes part of the mythology.

