**K-9's Reaction**: Mixed. Proud that SD Media is going international, but uneasy. Angel showed up from Oakland, got a feature with K-9, got Zed on the closing track, and now has a 7-track project that positions HIM as the voice of the label's next chapter. K-9 is THE Voice. That's his title. Hearing Angel call himself "the beat reverend" and "I teach the streets penmanship" — K-9 respects the bars but feels territorial. He won't say it out loud. He'll just go harder on his next track. The stutter-flow on Track 03 was K-9 at his most playful — but hearing the finished album back, K-9 realizes Angel kept the stumble in. Was that tribute or exposure? K-9's ad-libs on Track 05 were minimal for a reason — he was observing, not co-signing fully. After hearing the full project, K-9 tells Dame: "It's cold. But man's moving fast for a new dog."

**Zed's Reaction**: Silent approval. Zed gave Angel the benediction on Track 06. That doesn't happen lightly. Zed heard something in Angel that reminded him of himself — carrying dead weight, wearing masks, speaking in code. But Zed is also calculating. Angel's "Reyes Volkov" name on the album is dangerous — it mirrors Zed's Russian cover too closely. If anyone at the Academy hears both a "Russian student at NEPH" AND a "Volkov" on an SD Media album, questions get asked. Zed pulls Angel aside after the first listen: "The name. Change it or bury it. I don't care which. But it can't live on a track and live in a school at the same time." Angel pushes back. Zed doesn't repeat himself. The tension sits.

