**The Music Press**: UK grime publications are intrigued but cautious. An American on a grime track isn't new, but Angel isn't doing grime — he's doing something between grime, Bay Area hyphy, drill, and spoken word. There's no genre for it. One reviewer calls it "immigrant gospel." Another calls it "transatlantic threat music." The Poe reference on the title track gets picked up by a literary blog that has no idea what SD Media is — they just think the Tell-Tale Heart interpolation is clever. Suddenly Dog-Prophet has readers who've never heard grime in their lives.

**Oakland**: Word gets back to Ghost Town. Angel's old circle — what's left of it — has opinions. Some are proud (hometown kid went international). Some are suspicious (did he snitch his way to London? Is the album a cooperation agreement in disguise?). The dedications to Dimitri, Trey, Socks, and Yay on Track 01 either honor the dead or endanger the living, depending on who's listening. One of Angel's old associates sends a text: "Heard your thing. Sounds good. Take our names out." Angel doesn't reply. He can't. Those names are the only thing keeping those people alive in memory. Removing them would be its own kind of death.

**The Metropolitan Police**: If the album surfaces, it lands on a desk at the Met's Gangs Matrix unit within 48 hours. An analyst transcribes the Dog-Law commandments. They cross-reference "SD Media" with existing intelligence on the Stray Dogs. They note the cross-referencing of Oakland, Chicago, and London — which suggests international organized crime to anyone looking for it. They flag K-9's name. They flag Wormwood Scrubs. They add Angel Reyes to a watchlist. None of this results in immediate action — but it means the next time ANY dog does anything, the response will be heavier. The album doesn't cause a raid. It causes the raid after the raid to be worse.

---

### THE E-BOY FALLOUT

The single most dangerous element of the album isn't the RICO references or the Dog-Law commandments. It's Track 02. The E-Boy. Stray.

If anyone identifies The E-Boy's voice as Stray:
- It proves Stray is NOT silent — he's active under aliases
- It connects Stray to Angel (Oakland) and therefore to whatever Angel is running from
- It destroys Stray's carefully constructed anonymity
- It gives K-9 a reason to feel betrayed (Stray raps with a newcomer but won't record with the pack?)
- It gives Dame a crisis (she might have known; if she didn't, she'll be furious she wasn't told)
- It gives Big 9 validation (he always knew Stray had bars; this proves it)
- It gives Zed nothing new (Zed already knows everything)

The E-Boy is a loaded gun on a shelf. Every day the album stays vaulted is a day that gun doesn't go off. Every day it leaks closer to the surface is a day someone might recognize the voice that was supposed to stay silent.

---

### TRACK 08 CHANGES EVERYTHING

When Dame hears Track 08 for the first time — the FULL version, with the Lux dialogue, the 72 pills, the vodka from V's garage — she stops the playback. She doesn't walk out. She can't move. She sits in the producer chair and stares at the mixing board for a long time. Then she says, to no one: "He tried to die. He tried to die and then he flew to London and made an album." Dame has managed grief before — Big 9's sentencing, the funerals, the community losses. But this is different. This is a suicide survivor who put his attempt on tape. Dame doesn't vault the album after Track 08. She LOCKS it. There's a difference. Vaulted means waiting for the right time. Locked means she's not sure it should ever come out. She calls Big 9 that night. She doesn't play the track. She just says: "The Oakland kid tried to kill himself after his dad got shot. He put it on the album." Big 9 is quiet for thirty seconds. Then: "He's not leaving London. He stays with us. That's not a request."

K-9 hears Track 08 and goes silent. Not territorial. Not jealous. The silence of a 16-year-old who also has a brother in a cage, who also lost people, who also raps because stopping means drowning. But the suicide confession hits different. K-9 has heard Big 9 tell him online trolls said he should kill himself. K-9 has defended against that. But Angel actually DID it. Actually counted the pills — 72, two more than the bullets — and swallowed them with his dead father's vodka. K-9 doesn't speak to Angel for two days. Then he finds him at The Kennel and asks one question: "Your dad taught you to flow?" Angel nods. K-9: "Big 9 taught me." They sit together. K-9 doesn't bring up the pills. He doesn't need to. The fact that he's sitting next to Angel instead of across from him says everything.

Zed hears "70 shots to the chest" and his hand moves to his own scars — dragged three blocks, stabbed seven times. Zed knows overkill. Zed knows message killings. But when Zed hears the 72 pills, he goes completely still. Then he stands up and leaves The Kennel without a word. He comes back an hour later and hands Angel a piece of chalk. Doesn't explain. Angel looks at it. Zed: "When I wanted to die, I drew on walls instead. Keep it." Zed never mentions the Volkov name issue again. Some names need to stay on record.

Rax hears the album last because K-9 deliberately doesn't share it with him for a week. When Rax finally hears Track 08, he texts K-9: "Is he okay? Like actually okay?" K-9: "I think so. Dame's got him." Rax: "Bring him to the Plaza. He shouldn't be in a basement right now." K-9 doesn't reply, but the next day Angel is sitting at the coffee shop with Rax, not talking about music, just existing in daylight. Rax doesn't mention the track. He buys Angel a coffee and talks about lacrosse for an hour. It's the most normal Angel has felt since Oakland.

Chew-Toy hears it and immediately goes to Snout. This isn't about evidence files anymore. "The kid needs support. Real support. Not studio time — actual help." Snout, who doesn't do emotion, nods once. Within a week, Snout has quietly connected Angel with someone — not a therapist (Dogs don't do therapists), but an older community figure who lost a son to gun violence and survived. No paperwork. No referral. Just a phone number and the words: "Call him. He understands."

Lux never hears the released version of Track 08. Angel considers sending it. He opens the message three times. He can't. Because in the track, he calls her by her first name. He calls her "Lux" instead of "mom." And he confesses the 72 pills — which Lux found him seizing from, which Lux called the ambulance for, which Lux has never spoken about to anyone. If she hears it on a track, it becomes real in a way that living through it wasn't. Some things survive by never being named. Angel protects his mother the only way he knows how: by not letting her hear the truth she already lived through.

Big 9's final verdict, relayed through Dame: "That boy's not a new dog. He's an old dog in a young body. His father sent him to us. And we don't send people back."

